<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
This species is often collected with 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. phragmitidis" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="phragmitidis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">L. phragmitidis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Schrank, 1781) and 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. stigma" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="stigma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">L. stigma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Meigen, 1818), and it is a dominant species in Hemu (China: Xinjiang, Burqin). These species often aggregate in shaded understory plants in white birch forests during the day (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 45–47" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 45 - 47. Limonia sylvicola, male 45 male habitus, lateral view 46 head and thorax, dorsal view 47 right wing. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.971.35875.figures45-47" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/456146" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">46</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
